J. M. Smucker Co | North America

1Q disappointed vs. a high bar, but we view \(2\%\) OSG as solid & well above US food peers, while the unchanged FY EPS guide still appears conservative. Reiterate OW with visibility to sustained OSG and margin outperformance vs. center-store peers.

Reiterate OW: SJM shares declined \(\sim 450\) bps today (vs. S&P \(+20\) bps), which was not surprising given a high bar and a slight OSG miss ( \(\sim 80\) bps) with underlying trends, by our math, largely consistent with last quarter given some unexpected shipment headwinds despite accelerating coffee sales on higher pricing. Still, we view the \(+2\%\) OSG result in 1Q as solid in an absolute sense, and importantly well above most US center-store peers expected to report - LSD% declines while sustained strength in recent scanner trends and incremental coffee pricing provide good visibility into near-term acceleration. We also believe the 1Q volume miss is not reflective of underlying trends given it was dragged down by some temporary issues including promo timing in Sweet Baked Snacks and a tough compare for frozen handhelds/spreads. Moreover, contrary to our initial take this morning, we view the unchanged FY EPS guide as conservative, primarily on embedded coffee elasticity/margin assumptions, which management clarified are reflected in both the \(- \$ 0.60\) EPS headwind from coffee commodity inflation and the - \$0.50 headwind from tariffs. Bottom- line, we continue to like SJM's stock given what we see as a sustained acceleration in relative OSG momentum vs. food peers, supported by SJM's structurally advantaged portfolio in a challenging environment, idiosyncratic margin drivers into 2H26/FY27, and a highly visible deleveraging story. Post 1Q, we are lowering our FY26 EPS forecast by - LSD% but leaving our FY27 EPS estimate largely unchanged at \$10.66 ( \(\sim 16\%\) y/y growth), reflecting a more optimistic outlook on coffee as visibility into margin recovery improves.
Additional Takeaways and Conclusions Post the Call and Our Follow- Up with the Company:
FY26 EPS Guide Unchanged With Better Sales Offset by Incremental Gross Margin Pressure: SJM raised its FY26 net sales guidance to \(+3.0-\)

\(5.0\%\) Y/Y (vs. \(+2.0 - 4.0\%\) prior) and comparable net sales growth to \(+4.5-\) \(6.5\%\) (vs. \(+3.5 - 5.5\%\) prior), reflecting price up \(+10\%\) (vs. \(+9\%\) prior), partially offset by volume/mix down \(- 4\%\) (unchanged from prior). The \(- \$ 85M\) increase in the sales guide reflects a \(- \$ 100M\) increase in the coffee segment outlook offset by a slightly weaker outlook for the pet segment. The better sales outlook is being offset by incremental gross margin pressure due to higher tariffs with gross margin now guided to \(35.0 - 35.5\%\) (vs. \(35.5 - 36.0\%\) prior)

with overall gross profit \~unchanged. Net, the EPS guide of \$8.50- 9.50 is unchanged, but is now more back half weighted vs. prior expectations, with 2Q gross margin expected to trough closer to \~34% (vs. Street at 35.8%) due to green coffee hedging/inventory timing.

- 2Q EPS Expected to Decline 25% Y/Y: This is below SJM's prior expectations and is driven primarily by a lower expectation for coffee gross profits due to hedging/inventory receipt timing mismatch and is expected to result in sequentially lower gross margins in 2Q. However, this is primarily a timing shift in profits to the 2H of the year with 3Q/4Q expected to show sequential improvement and coffee margins expected to exit the year in the \~mid-20% range.

- US Retail Coffee: SJM now expects FY26 coffee pricing in the mid-20% range (vs. low-20% prior), with 2Q and 3Q price in the mid-20% range and 4Q closer to 30%. Coffee volumes are expected to decline low-to-mid teens % for the FY, resulting in overall segment OSG up +low-to-mid-teens %. Elasticities in 1Q came in better than modeled, delivering \~\(50M in upside. SJM is assuming -0.5 elasticity for its August price increase (in-line with history), and greater than historical elasticity for the anticipated winter price increase. The additional pricing and better elasticity result in 1Q is driving\)0.20 of EPS improvement vs. SJM's prior expectation, resulting in a net unfavorable impact of -\(0.60 (vs. -\)0.80 prior). This is offset by an incremental -\(0.25 of green coffee tariff pressure, bringing the total FY26 tariff-related EPS impact to -\)0.50. 2Q coffee gross profit will be negatively impacted by green coffee hedge/inventory timing mismatch, but profit expectation for the full year is unchanged, implying 2H profit weighting, with margins expected to be in the low 20% in 3Q and mid-20% in 4Q.

- Sweet Baked Snacks: Hostess trends remain weak, with 1Q26 OSG down - 10%, though management commentary was rather constructive noting "green shoots" in the convenience channel and strong share trends at key mass and traditional retail partners. Management continues to expect sequential improvement in the segment with 2Q expected to improve to a -L-MSD% decline with 3Q stabilizing and a potential return to growth in the 4Q. Segment profits also expected to improve through the balance of the year, with 4Q being the strongest, aided by the closure of the Indianapolis facility, which is expected to generate \$10M in savings in 4Q26 and \$20M in FY27, for a total of \$30M in run-rate savings.

- US Retail Frozen Handheld & Spreads: 1Q26 OSG performance of down -2% Y/Y was impacted by tough companies in Jif and a promo timing shift, as well as lapping strong distribution gains for Uncrustables. SJM still expect MSD% net sales growth for the FY, with 2Q up LSD% as Uncrustables pricing flows through, with the 2H up MSD% driven by stabilization in fruit spreads and Jif on easier companies.
- US Retail Pet Food: Pet trends remain soft, with 1Q OSG of -8% driven by decreases for dog snacks due to fewer treating frequencies. SJM reduced its

net sales expectations for its dog snacks portfolio. Primary in Pupperoni and Canine Carry Outs brands, partly offset by an acceleration in Milk- Bone, which SJM expects will return to net sales growth in 2H. Added by easing compares. SJM expects 2Q segment OSG down MSD%, while 3Q and 4Q will be up MSD% as the company laps supply chain disruption and inventory destocking, resulting in FY OSG fls down slightly (vs. flat to up slightly prior).

- FCF: SJM raised its FY26 FCF guidance to \(975M\) (vs. \(875M\) prior), benefiting from bonus depreciation and accelerated R&D deductibility under the One Big Beautiful Bill Act, which will be an ongoing annual benefit on a go-forward basis. SJM says the incremental cash flow will be used to support ongoing debt paydown, with a leverage ratio target of 3.0x by end of FY27 (vs. 4.3x currently).

Updates to Our Model: For FY26, we now model \(+5.7\%\) OSG (vs. \(+5.0\%\) prior), adj gross margin of \(35.8\%\) (vs. \(36.3\%\) prior), adj EBITDA of \(2,020M\) (vs. \(2,060M\) prior), and adj EPS of \(9.19\) (vs. \(9.53\) prior). For FY27, we now model \(+3.3\%\) OSG (vs. \(+2.5\%\) prior), adj gross margin of \(37.1\%\) (vs. \(37.3\%\) prior), adj EBITDA of \(2,183M\) (vs. \(2,177M\) prior), and adj EPS of \(10.66\) (vs. \(10.63\) prior). Our price target is unchanged at \(118, based on an average of 11.5x P/E and 9.5x EV/EBITDA.
